    Date: Wed, 6 Aug 86 08:40:23 edt
    From: Liudvikas Bukys  &lt;bukys@rochester.arpa&gt;

    Since the current canonical form for transport (for a fully-qualified name) is
    "no trailing dot", then the user interface should also use this convention.
    Otherwise, poor users will always be wondering what they have when someone
    sends them an address, or when they pluck an address out of an existing
    message.  (If we had to do it over again, I would have put a trailing dot at
    the root of a fully-qualified name, but it's too late for that now.)

Here we go with envelopes versus messages.  The presentation of the
envelope should be under control of the user agent program.  If we
believe that the across-the-net syntax is independent of the user
interface, then we need strong statements that users should never see
raw envelope data -- some agent should be turning it into
human-comprenensible form.  If that means reversing the ends, adding a
rooting character, or whatever, then so be it.

If we believe that there will never be real user interfaces, then we had
best redesign the net format to be person-friendly.

    Given that, we need a way to recognize partially-qualified names.  I nominate
    the ellipsis "...".  While one dot will forever be suggesting an absolute root,
    three dots is a very natural notation for "there's more...".

    Liudvikas Bukys

